In LaTeX, generating a table of contents (ToC) automatically is straightforward. Here's a simple example showcasing how to create a table of contents in a LaTeX document:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section.

\section{Related Work}
This is the related work section.

\section{Methodology}
This is the methodology section.

\section{Experiments}
This is the experiments section.

\section{Results}
This is the results section.

\section{Discussion}
This is the discussion section.

\end{document}
```

In the above example, we use the `\tableofcontents` command to generate the table of contents. The sections in our document are created using `\section` commands, each with a unique title. When you compile this LaTeX document, it will automatically generate a table of contents listing all the sections with their respective page numbers.

Here's a brief explanation of the commands used:

1. `\documentclass{article}`: This command sets up the document class, in this case, `article`.
2. `\begin{document}` and `\end{document}`: These commands mark the beginning and end of the LaTeX document.
3. `\tableofcontents`: This command generates the table of contents.
4. `\section{Title}`: This command creates a new section with the specified title.

Make sure to compile your LaTeX document using a LaTeX compiler such as `pdflatex` or `xelatex` to generate the PDF output. The table of contents will be automatically updated each time you compile the document, reflecting any changes you make to the sections.

To draw a chessboard in LaTeX using a FEN notation, we can use the `chessfss` package, which provides a way to specify FEN notation and draw the corresponding chessboard.

Here's an example of how to draw a chessboard in LaTeX given a FEN notation:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessfss}

\begin{document}

\begin{chessfss}
  [FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
  \chessboard
\end{chessfss}

\end{document}
```

In this example, the FEN notation is provided within the `[FEN ...]` command inside the `\begin{chessfss}` and `\end{chessfss}` environment. The FEN notation describes the state of the chessboard, including piece positions, colors, castling rights, en passant target square, half move clock, and full move number.

When you compile this LaTeX code, it will generate a PDF file showing the chessboard in the specified state. You can replace the FEN notation with any valid FEN string to display different chessboard states.

Make sure to install the `chessfss` package before compiling the LaTeX code. You can do this by running `tlmgr install chessfss` in a terminal or by downloading the package from the CTAN repository and installing it manually.

Keep in mind that the `chessfss` package uses the font `ChessFontSF`, which might not be available on all systems. If you encounter any issues with missing fonts, you may need to install the font manually or use a different package like `chessboard` that provides a more standard approach to drawing chessboards in LaTeX.

